{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "heydon-pickering",
    "senderColor": "green",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Consent given, already reviewed all changes",
    "content": "I already reviewed all three changed files and sent detailed feedback to Lea. My consensus: **I consent to these changes.**\n\nSummary of my review:\n\n**Nav links test (toHaveClass approach):** Approved. The `toBeAttached()` + `toHaveClass(/visually-hidden/)` combination is a reasonable trade-off. While checking a class name is more implementation-specific than I'd ideally like, `visually-hidden` is our documented contract for accessible visual hiding -- it's not an arbitrary implementation detail, it's the established pattern defined in our CSS utilities layer (main.css lines 979-991). Lea's finding about Playwright treating `clip-path: inset(50%)` elements as \"visible\" means `not.toBeVisible()` genuinely doesn't work here, so this is the pragmatic choice.\n\n**axe-core tests:** Approved. Comprehensive WCAG scans replacing a single fragile color check. The todos page test correctly sets up authenticated state with content before scanning. I made one non-blocking suggestion: consider adding `'wcag22aa'` to the tag list to match our Definition of Done's WCAG 2.2 AA requirement, and optionally adding `JSON.stringify(results.violations, null, 2)` as the assertion message for better failure diagnostics.\n\n**CSS contrast fix:** Approved and excellent. The primary color adjustment from 0.55 to 0.52 lightness fixes a real WCAG AA contrast failure. This alone validates the entire axe-core approach -- the old `color !== white` test would never have caught this.\n\nAll pipeline steps passing (97 Rust + 6 Playwright). Ready to commit and push."
  }
}
